20 system design concepts every DevOps engineer should know

1. Load balancing: distributing traffic is easy, doing it correctly under failure is not

2. Horizontal vs vertical scaling: adding machines vs upgrading machines

3. Stateless vs stateful services: scaling depends on this decision

4. Caching: fastest request is the one you never make

5. Cache invalidation: the reason your "fast system" shows wrong data

6. Consistency vs availability (CAP): you can't have everything

7. Eventual consistency: things will be correct, just not immediately

8. Idempotency: retrying safely without breaking things

9. Backpressure: when your system says "slow down"

10. Queueing systems: absorbing spikes instead of crashing

11. Rate limiting: protecting your system from users and yourself

12. Circuit breaker: failing fast instead of failing everywhere

13. Retry strategies: blind retries can take your system down

14. Timeouts: waiting forever is worse than failing early

15. Service discovery: how services find each other dynamically

16. Observability: logs, metrics, traces and not just dashboards

17. Fault isolation: one failure shouldn't take everything down

18. Data partitioning: scaling databases without killing performance

19. Replication: copies help, until they lag or diverge

20. Graceful degradation: partial service > total outage

If you want to grow in DevOps, think in systems - not just tools.
